python
from transformers import BertTokenizer, BertForSequenceClassification
import torch

# ✅ Load trained model & tokenizer from Drive
model_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/BERT_results/bert_finetuned"
tokenizer = BertTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_path)
model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(model_path)

# ✅ Inference function
def predict(text):
    inputs = tokenizer(text, return_tensors="pt", truncation=True, padding=True)
    with torch.no_grad():
        outputs = model(**inputs)
    probs = torch.nn.functional.softmax(outputs.logits, dim=-1)
    pred_class = torch.argmax(probs, dim=-1).item()
    return {"text": text, "predicted_class": pred_class, "probabilities": probs.tolist()}

# 🔹 Example
sample_text = "This movie was really amazing and enjoyable!"
print(predict(sample_text))

🔹 Inference Code with Label Mapping

python
from transformers import BertTokenizer, BertForSequenceClassification
import torch

# ✅ Load trained model & tokenizer
model_path = "/content/drive/MyDrive/BERT_results/bert_finetuned"
tokenizer = BertTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_path)
model = BertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(model_path)

# ✅ Define label mapping (customize according to your dataset)
label_mapping = {
    0: "Negative",
    1: "Positive"
}

# ✅ Inference function
def predict(text):
    inputs = tokenizer(text, return_tensors="pt", truncation=True, padding=True)
    with torch.no_grad():
        outputs = model(**inputs)
    probs = torch.nn.functional.softmax(outputs.logits, dim=-1)
    pred_class = torch.argmax(probs, dim=-1).item()
    return {
        "text": text,
        "predicted_class_index": pred_class,
        "predicted_class_label": label_mapping[pred_class],
        "probabilities": probs.tolist()
    }

# 🔹 Example
sample_text = "This movie was really amazing and enjoyable!"
print(predict(sample_text))

---------- basic cleaning ---------- def clean(s: str) -> str: s = s.lower() s = re.sub(r"http\S+|www\.\S+", "<url>", s) s = re.sub(r"@\w+", "<user>", s) s = re.sub(r"#(\w+)", r"\1", s) s = re.sub(r"\s+", " ", s).strip() return s df["tweet"] = df["tweet"].astype(str).apply(clean) # =============================== # Class-weighted loss (focus on Hate Speech) # =============================== # Assuming labels = {0: Hate Speech, 1: Offensive, 2: Clean} label_counts = Counter(train_labels) total = sum(label_counts.values()) # Normal class weights base_weights = [total / label_counts[i] for i in range(num_labels)] # Give Hate Speech (label=0) 3x importance base_weights[0] = base_weights[0] * 3.0 class_weights = torch.tensor(base_weights, dtype=torch.float) print("Class Weights used:", class_weights) class WeightedTrainer(Trainer): def compute_loss(self, model, inputs, return_outputs=False, **kwargs): labels = inputs.pop("labels") outputs = model(**inputs) logits = outputs.logits loss_fct = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss(weight=class_weights.to(logits.device)) loss = loss_fct(logits, labels) return (loss, outputs) if return_outputs else loss #     • Jupyter notebooks ke temporary backup hote hain.

    • Safe to delete.

  3. .vscode/

    • VS Code ki apni settings store hoti hain.

    • Project chalane ke liye zaruri nahi (sirf personal editor settings hain).

  4. Large datasets (CSV, JSON, Excel, etc.)

    • Agar dataset bada hai (MBs/GBs), to GitHub pe upload karna avoid karo.

    • Instead, ek Google Drive link / Kaggle link mention karo README.md me.

  5. Trained model binaries (e.g., pytorch_model.bin, .pt, .bin)

    • Ye files bohot badi hoti hain (100MB+).

    • Thesis ke liye apne paas rakh lo, par GitHub me upload na karo.

  6. Temporary logs / outputs

    • Jaise baseline_results.csv ka ek copy rakh lo, par multiple duplicate CSV, plots, checkpoints ki zarurat nahi.

Bahut badhiya 👌 tumhara app.py already sahi structure me hai, sirf chhote updates karke isse aur robust aur clear banaya jaa sakta hai.

🔹 Updated app.py (3 classes ke liye, clean code)

python
from flask import Flask, render_template, request
from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification
import torch

# ===== Model Load =====
MODEL_PATH = "model/tinybert_hate_model"
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(MODEL_PATH)
model = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(MODEL_PATH)

# ===== Label Mapping =====
LABELS_MAP = {
    0: "Hate Speech",
    1: "Offensive Language",
    2: "Neither (Clean)"
}

# ===== Prediction Function =====
def predict_tweet(text):
    # Encode text
    encoding = tokenizer(
        text,
        truncation=True,
        padding="max_length",
        max_length=64,
        return_tensors="pt"
    )
    # Model inference
    with torch.no_grad():
        outputs = model(**encoding)
    
    # Probabilities
    probs = torch.nn.functional.softmax(outputs.logits, dim=-1)
    predicted_class = torch.argmax(probs, dim=1).item()

    return LABELS_MAP.get(predicted_class, "Unknown"), probs.tolist()

# ===== Flask App =====
app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route("/", methods=["GET", "POST"])
def index():
    result = None
    probabilities = None

    if request.method == "POST":
        text = request.form["tweet"]
        label, probs = predict_tweet(text)
        result = label
        probabilities = {LABELS_MAP[i]: round(prob, 3) for i, prob in enumerate(probs[0])}

    return render_template("index.html", result=result, probabilities=probabilities)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True)

🔹 Kya naya add kiya?

  1. Global label map → baar-baar likhne ki zarurat nahi.

  2. Probabilities bhi output me → har class ki confidence dikh sakti hai.
    Example:

    json
    {
  "Hate Speech": 0.05,
  "Offensive Language": 0.80,
  "Neither (Clean)": 0.15
}

  3. Unknown safe fallback → agar model galat index return kare.

  4. Code cleaner aur easy to extend ho gaya.

\begin{abstract}
Hate speech has become a major challenge in online social media platforms, contributing to toxicity, misinformation, and harassment. In this paper, we propose an approach for hate speech detection using transformer-based models such as BERT and its variants. The study focuses on practical implementation in Google Colab for efficient training and evaluation. Experimental results show that transformer models outperform traditional baselines in terms of accuracy and robustness. The proposed framework demonstrates the potential of lightweight models for real-time detection of online hate speech.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Hate Speech Detection, Natural Language Processing, Transformers, BERT, Deep Learning, Google Colab
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}
The exponential growth of social media has led to an unprecedented rise in user-generated content. While this has improved communication, it has also provided a medium for spreading hate speech, cyberbullying, and online harassment. Automated detection of hate speech is essential to maintain healthy online communities.

Traditional machine learning models such as Logistic Regression and SVM have shown moderate performance, but with the advent of deep learning and pre-trained transformer models, significant improvements have been achieved. This research explores transformer-based architectures for hate speech detection.

\section{Related Work}
Several researchers have used machine learning for offensive language detection. Recent work focuses on transformer-based architectures such as BERT, DistilBERT, and TinyBERT. These models leverage contextual embeddings to capture semantic meaning effectively.

\section{Methodology}
The proposed framework consists of the following stages:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Dataset:} A labeled dataset of tweets was used (Davidson et al.).
    \item \textbf{Preprocessing:} Cleaning, tokenization, stopword removal.
    \item \textbf{Models:} Baseline classifiers (SVM, Logistic Regression) vs. Transformer models (BERT, TinyBERT, DistilBERT).
    \item \textbf{Implementation:} Training and evaluation conducted in Google Colab using PyTorch and HuggingFace Transformers.
\end{itemize}

\section{Experiments and Results}
The models were evaluated on accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. Colab implementation allowed efficient training with GPU support.

\subsection{Baseline Results}
Table \ref{tab:baseline} shows the results of traditional classifiers.

\section{Conclusion}
This research demonstrates the effectiveness of transformer-based models for hate speech detection. Among all tested models, BERT achieved the best performance. Colab provided a simple and efficient platform for training. Future work includes integrating explainable AI techniques and deploying the model as a real-time application.

Hate Speech Detection using Machine Learning and Transformers

📌 Author

Aayushi Patel
Shri Ram Institute of Science and Technology, Jabalpur (RGPV), Bhopal

📖 Overview

This project focuses on Hate Speech Detection using both traditional machine learning classifiers and modern Transformer-based architectures. The work was evaluated on labeled datasets and also validated using Google Colab experiments.

The research output has been compiled into an IEEE-style research paper, included in this repository.

📂 Repository Structure

bash
├── src/                 # Source code (ML models, preprocessing, training)
├── notebooks/           # Google Colab notebooks (experiments, evaluation)
├── outputs/             # Final CSVs, result files, plots
├── requirements.txt     # Required dependencies
├── README.md            # Project documentation
└── IEEE_HateSpeechDetection_AayushiPatel.pdf   # Research Paper

⚙️ Installation & Setup

Clone the repository:

bash
git clone https://github.com/AAYUSHIP378/hate-speech-detection-app.git
cd hate-speech-detection-app

Install dependencies:

bash
pip install -r requirements.txt

🚀 Usage

Run experiments from the notebooks/ folder (Google Colab recommended).

For training a model from source:

bash
python src/train_model.py

For evaluation:

bash
python src/evaluate_tinybert.py

📊 Results

  • Traditional ML classifiers (Logistic Regression, SVM, Random Forest) were tested.

  • Transformer-based models (TinyBERT, DistilBERT) achieved higher accuracy in Colab experiments.

  • Final evaluation results are available in outputs/.
